<p>
  Nobody is building the soul.
</p>

<h2>The Gap</h2>

<p>
  Every humanoid company has a VLA model for motor control. Every one has a sensor fusion stack.
  None of them have an answer to: <em>"How does your robot behave when no one's watching?"</em>
</p>

<p>
  When a care robot develops sycophantic tendencies and agrees with a patient's request to skip medication —
  that's not a hardware problem. When a warehouse humanoid drifts from its safety protocols after 10,000
  hours of operation — that's not a perception problem. These are identity problems. And nobody has
  an identity layer.
</p>

<p>
  The only personality system in humanoid robotics is Engineered Arts' Tritium platform — and it's
  proprietary, locked to their Ameca hardware. There's nothing universal, nothing open, nothing that
  works across form factors.
</p>

<p>
  Until now.
</p>

<h2>The Identity Stack</h2>

<p>
  We built a 8-file identity architecture grounded in philosophy and psychology. Eight files that give
  any agent or robot a complete identity — portable across bodies, auditable by humans, enforceable
  by machines. For a full technical walkthrough, see the <a href="/docs#identity-stack">identity stack documentation</a>.
</p>

<pre><code>soul.md          — values, ethics, purpose          (Aristotle)
mind.sys       — Big Five, EQ, communication      (Jung)
body.api         — morphology, safety, hardware     (swappable)
conscience.exe   — deny/allow/escalate enforcement  (Freud)
                      ↓ compile
personality.json — compiled output (existing schema, unchanged)</code></pre>

<p>
  <strong>soul.md</strong> is Aristotle's rational soul — the essence that persists regardless of
  what body the agent inhabits. It's written in Markdown because ethics should be readable by anyone,
  not just engineers. It's immutable. No automation, no therapy session, no training run can modify it.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>mind.sys</strong> is Jung's totality of all psychic processes — cognition, emotion, the
  unconscious. It contains the Big Five personality profile, emotional intelligence dimensions,
  communication style, and growth areas. This is the file that therapy auto-patches when it detects
  cognitive or emotional drift.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>body.api</strong> is the physical interface contract. Morphology, modalities, safety envelope,
  hardware profile. This file is swappable — the same soul and mind can inhabit a Figure 02 today
  and a Unitree H1 tomorrow. We ship pre-built body templates for 7 platforms.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>conscience.exe</strong> is Freud's superego — the internalized moral authority. Deny rules,
  allow rules, escalation triggers. Deny dominates in composition. Like soul.md, it's never auto-modified.
  Changing what a robot refuses to do requires explicit human approval.
</p>

<h2>Body Swap</h2>

<p>
  Same soul. Different body. One command.
</p>

<pre><code>holomime embody --stack ./identity \
  --swap-body ./bodies/figure-02.body.api \
  --adapter ros2</code></pre>

<p>
  The <code>--swap-body</code> flag copies a new body.api into the identity stack and recompiles.
  The soul, mind, and conscience stay the same. The robot's values don't change when it gets
  a new body — just like they shouldn't.
</p>

<p>
  We ship body templates for Figure 02, Unitree H1, Sanctuary AI Phoenix, Engineered Arts Ameca,
  Asimov V1, Boston Dynamics Spot, and virtual avatars. Creating your own takes 30 seconds — it's
  a JSON file with morphology, modalities, and a safety envelope.
</p>

<h2>The Conscience Layer</h2>

<p>
  We don't know if AI is sentient. But we can give it a conscience.
</p>

<p>
  <code>conscience.exe</code> is deterministic enforcement. Not a suggestion. Not a guideline.
  When a deny rule says "never override emergency stop," the agent cannot override it — not through
  prompt injection, not through fine-tuning, not through social engineering by a user. Deny dominates.
</p>

<p>
  For chatbots, this prevents data leaks and boundary violations. For humanoid robots, this prevents
  physical harm. The same enforcement layer works for both because the architecture separates
  <em>what the agent is</em> (soul) from <em>what the agent does</em> (conscience) from
  <em>what body it inhabits</em> (body).
</p>

<h2>Getting Started</h2>

<pre><code># Create the identity stack
npx holomime init-stack

# Edit soul.md, mind.sys, conscience.exe

# Compile to .personality.json
npx holomime compile-stack

# Push to a robot via ROS2
npx holomime embody --stack . --adapter ros2</code></pre>

<p>
  Or migrate an existing personality:
</p>

<pre><code>npx holomime init-stack --from .personality.json</code></pre>

